==English==
{{wikipedia}}
===Etymology===
From Latin [[anachronismus]] < Greek [[αναχρονισμός]] < [[αναχρονίζειν]] (referring to the wrong time) < [[ἀνά]] (up against) + [[χρονίζειν]] (spending time) < [[χρόνος]] (time).

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

# [[Artifact]], that which belongs to a [[time]] that has already past.
# A person who seems to belong to another time.
# A person who seems to belong to another age.
# Something that is out of [[chronological]] order.
# A representation of something that is out of chronological order.
# An event in time that has no explanation for why it could have occured.
# An object in time that has no explanation for why it could have been there.
# Neglect; falsification.

====Quotations====
*'''1956''' — [[w:Arthur C. Clarke|Arthur C. Clarke]], ''The City and the Stars'', p 32
*:His movements, his clothes, everything about him, seemed slightly out of place in this assembly. He spoiled the pattern; like Alvin, he was an '''anachronism'''.

